---
/**
 * NetworkSection — network-effect / continual-learning explainer.
 *
 * Positions the platform's differentiator honestly: yes, Lumecon
 * trains on customer data (with permission) — that's the whole
 * point of a network that compounds. What the visitor needs to
 * trust is that the SHAPE of that training is anonymised and
 * aggregated across the network, and that their own workspace
 * results stay theirs.
 *
 * The incumbent posture is different: existing economic-impact
 * tools ship administrative data as a static product on a
 * multi-year vintage cycle. We don't claim they refuse to learn —
 * that's not the kind of thing you can prove from outside — but
 * leading with what we DO lets visitors draw the comparison.
 *
 * Important: any "data never leaves your workspace" wording is
 * misleading. We do train on customer data. The honest framing is:
 * (1) results in your workspace are yours, (2) cross-customer
 * learning runs on anonymised aggregates, (3) the result is that
 * every new client makes the next study sharper for everyone.
 */
import '../styles/network.css';
---
<section class="network" id="network" aria-labelledby="network-title">
  <div class="network-inner">
    <div class="network-text">
      <p class="network-kicker">The network</p>
      <h2 class="network-title reveal-soft hl-block hl-block--b" id="network-title">Your work stays yours. The model gets sharper for everyone.</h2>
      <p class="network-lede">Every new client makes every other client's next economic impact study a little better. We train on the network: anonymised, aggregated signals across thousands of studies. The regional multipliers, the assumption defaults, and Cedar's harmonization rules keep tightening as more organizations join.</p>

      <ul class="network-points">
        <li class="network-point">
          <h3 class="network-point__head">Anonymised, aggregated training</h3>
          <p class="network-point__body">Cross-customer learning runs on anonymised aggregates, not row-level uploads. Identifiers, sensitive fields, and study-specific labels are stripped before any signal reaches the shared model.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="network-point">
          <h3 class="network-point__head">Your workspace is yours</h3>
          <p class="network-point__body">Your raw files, your study outputs, and your audit trail stay in your tenant. What you publish is what you choose to publish; the network sees patterns, not your specific results.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="network-point">
          <h3 class="network-point__head">Compounds with every economic impact study</h3>
          <p class="network-point__body">More historic studies on file, more current studies running, more geographies covered. Each one tightens the next regional multiplier estimate and the next Cedar harmonization pass. The incumbents treat administrative data as a static product; we treat the network as a living signal.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Asymmetric, evolving network. Not a tidy mesh — eleven
         nodes scattered off-grid, twenty edges, sized irregularly.
         The animation is sequenced rather than rhythmic: a few
         seed nodes appear, then growth nodes spawn and connect,
         a hub forms, late nodes fill in the periphery, and the
         whole network breathes briefly before fading and looping.
         Each node "fills in" with accent shortly after its edges
         connect so the visual reads as "this participant joined
         and is now part of the network," not a decorative pulse. -->
    <div class="network-diagram" aria-hidden="true">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 240 240" fill="none" class="netv2">
        <g class="netv2__edges" stroke-linecap="round" fill="none">
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--ab" x1="28"  y1="56"  x2="82"  y2="38"  pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--ac" x1="28"  y1="56"  x2="54"  y2="110" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--bc" x1="82"  y1="38"  x2="54"  y2="110" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--bd" x1="82"  y1="38"  x2="130" y2="60"  pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--cd" x1="54"  y1="110" x2="130" y2="60"  pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--de" x1="130" y1="60"  x2="174" y2="92"  pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--ef" x1="174" y1="92"  x2="210" y2="50"  pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--df" x1="130" y1="60"  x2="210" y2="50"  pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--cj" x1="54"  y1="110" x2="38"  y2="188" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--aj" x1="28"  y1="56"  x2="38"  y2="188" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--cg" x1="54"  y1="110" x2="96"  y2="156" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--gj" x1="96"  y1="156" x2="38"  y2="188" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--dk" x1="130" y1="60"  x2="118" y2="116" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--ek" x1="174" y1="92"  x2="118" y2="116" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--kg" x1="118" y1="116" x2="96"  y2="156" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--kh" x1="118" y1="116" x2="152" y2="180" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--ak" x1="28"  y1="56"  x2="118" y2="116" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--gh" x1="96"  y1="156" x2="152" y2="180" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--hi" x1="152" y1="180" x2="192" y2="158" pathLength="100"/>
          <line class="netv2__edge netv2__edge--ei" x1="174" y1="92"  x2="192" y2="158" pathLength="100"/>
        </g>
        <g class="netv2__nodes">
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--A"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--A" cx="28"  cy="56"  r="6.5"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--B"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--B" cx="82"  cy="38"  r="5.5"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--C"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--C" cx="54"  cy="110" r="8"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--D"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--D" cx="130" cy="60"  r="5"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--E"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--E" cx="174" cy="92"  r="7"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--F"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--F" cx="210" cy="50"  r="4"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--G"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--G" cx="96"  cy="156" r="6"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--H"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--H" cx="152" cy="180" r="7"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--I"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--I" cx="192" cy="158" r="5"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--J"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--J" cx="38"  cy="188" r="4.5"/></g>
          <g class="netv2__bob netv2__bob--K"><circle class="netv2__node netv2__node--K" cx="118" cy="116" r="10"/></g>
        </g>
      </svg>
      <!-- Footnote under the diagram: how cross-customer learning
           works without shipping row-level files around. Smaller
           type so it reads as a methodology note rather than a
           competing block of prose. -->
      <p class="network-diagram__note">We use methods we developed in-house to capture the benefits of federated learning with coarse, anonymised data only. Raw records never leave your workspace; the shared model learns from aggregate signals across thousands of studies.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
